h3. Issue Summary

Legacy Automation webhook attachment content URL changes intermittently.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
Unable to reproduce, but the step is to:
 # Create Legacy automation to send webhook to remote server
!image-2021-12-24-12-27-51-409.png|width=400!

h3. Expected Results

Expected attachment content URL is "/secure/attachment/10021/test-image.png" like below.
{code:java}
{
    "issue": {
    ...
        "attachment": [
          {
            "self": "https://test.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/attachment/10021",
            ...
            "content": "https://test.atlassian.net/secure/attachment/10021/test-image.png",
          }
        ]
    ...
  }
}
{code}
h3. Actual Results

Sometimes the URL of attachment content is "/rest/api/2/attachment/content/10021" like below.
{code:java}
{
    "issue": {
    ...
        "attachment": [
          {
            "self": "https://test.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/attachment/10021",
            ...
            "content": "https://test.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/attachment/content/10021",
          }
        ]
    ...
  }
}
{code}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

The LIKE operator is okay for some purposes, but my users are asking for wildcard characters when they search in Insight.

 

In their previous asset tracking solution, a common task was to search the database with very specific characters as variable, which would return all of a set or a series based on our naming convention. For example:

 
{code:java}
// code WHERE SerialNo LIKE 'HM-__-51';{code}
or

 
{code:java}
// code WHERE PropertyID LIKE '01%BFL2%';
{code}
 


Using the LIKE operator would return matches that contain BFL2 anywhere in the field, and not in the exact position desired.

 

My users are also accustomed to common windows search wildcards such a \*.txt or DCIM\*.jpg and have asked for similar functionality in Insight's quick search feature.

We use the following endpoint to fetch articles from a specific knowledge base:
{code:java}
/rest/servicedeskapi/servicedesk/${serviceDeskId}/knowledgebase/article?query=${query}&limit=10{code}
We'd like to be able to pass in multiple service desk ids to fetch articles from.

Currently, we have cases where we have to make one request per knowledge base. While it's possible to not pass in an id and fetch results from all knowledge bases in one go, we have customers that haven't connected all their knowledge bases to our product.

The issue is amplified if the user is a slow typer. e.g. searching for "query" in 20 knowledge bases results in 100 requests.
